{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d877c1a9-d740-44b0-b755-315973e594a2","content":"## What's happening\n\n.NET has been progressively raising its minimum x86-64 CPU instruction set requirements. Your 2012-era hardware likely predates **Haswell** (launched mid-2013), meaning it's a **Sandy Bridge** or **Ivy Bridge** processor. These CPUs support up to **x86-64-v2** but lack the **x86-64-v3** instructions (AVX2, BMI1/2, FMA, F16C, LZCNT, MOVBE).\n\nWhen .NET 11 raised its x86-64 baseline to **x86-64-v3**, pre-Haswell CPUs started failing the runtime's startup instruction set check — producing exactly this error.\n\n## Your other platforms\n\n| Target | Impact |\n|---|---|\n| **Linux x86-64 (post-2013 hardware)** | ✅ Fine — Haswell+ supports x86-64-v3 |\n| **Linux x86-64 (2012 hardware)** | ❌ **Fails** — pre-Haswell, no AVX2/BMI/FMA |\n| **Windows Arm64 (Surface Pro X / SQ1)** | ✅ Fine — Arm64 has its own baseline, unaffected by x86-64 level changes |\n| **Raspberry Pi 4 (Linux Arm32/Arm64)** | ✅ Fine — ARM architecture, not affected |\n\n## What you can do\n\n1. **Retire or replace** the pre-Haswell nodes (they're 13+ years old).\n2. **Stay on .NET 10** for workloads that must run on that hardware, while upgrading everything else.\n3. **Check your CPU** on the failing node: `lscpu | grep -E 'Model name|Flags'` — confirm it lacks `avx2`, `bmi1`, `bmi2`, `fma`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b8782495-7642-4eee-8401-c6997fe08c31","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements changes.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nStarting with .NET 9 (and continuing into later versions), Microsoft has been raising the baseline CPU instruction set requirements for x86-64. Specifically:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier: The x86-64 baseline was the original x86-64 (AMD64) instruction set, which is essentially x86-64-v1.\n- .NET 9: Microsoft considered raising the baseline but ultimately kept compatibility.\n\n\n- There have been discussions about requiring x86-64-v2 or even x86-64-v3 as the baseline.\n\nThe x86-64 microarchitecture levels define different CPU capability tiers: v1 is the original baseline with SSE and SSE2, v2 adds later instruction sets like SSE4.2 and POPCNT from around 2008 onwards, and v3 includes AVX and AVX2 support for more modern processors.\n\nThe critical point is that hardware from 2012 like Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge only supports up to v2—they lack the AVX2, BMI, and FMA instructions that v3 requires. If .NET 11 shifted its Linux baseline to v3, older CPUs from that era would immediately fail with this exact error.\n\nI should be careful here though—.NET 11 hasn't actually released yet, so I'm speculating about its requirements. But the user is experiencing a real problem, and the most likely explanation based on .NET's trajectory is that a newer runtime version raised the CPU baseline beyond what their hardware supports. I don't have definitive details on .NET 11's exact CPU baseline since it may not be fully documented yet, but the pattern is clear: newer .NET versions are raising the x86-64 instruction set requirements, and hardware from 2012 (Sandy Bridge/Ivy Bridge) simply doesn't support the AVX2 and other SIMD instructions that the newer baseline demands. I can explain the mechanism and likely cause without needing to look anything up. raised the baseline to x86-64-v3, which would exclude any CPUs older than Haswell. That's the most likely culprit for why 2012 hardware is suddenly failing with .NET 11.","outputTokens":1812,"requestId":"8862:26D998:1EF00E8:226017A:69FA9CF0"},"id":"7e4d78ae-b345-4527-bb16-a01b5b04edc6","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:44:53.004Z","parentId":"a88b2bcd-c6a5-4c00-9925-3f0cc9dfd199"}
